WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:06.285 --> 00:00:08.187
<i>Previously on</i>
Criminal Minds: Evolution...

2
00:00:08.287 --> 00:00:10.121
Everything okay?

3
00:00:10.222 --> 00:00:12.324
Henry got into San Diego.

4
00:00:13.792 --> 00:00:15.494
With whom do we have
the pleasure of speaking?

5
00:00:15.594 --> 00:00:17.196
<i>Call me God.</i>

6
00:00:17.296 --> 00:00:20.699
I recognize that voice.
It's Lance Kingston.

7
00:00:20.799 --> 00:00:22.601
<i>But he can't be our guy.</i>

8
00:00:22.701 --> 00:00:23.702
<i>He's his hostage.</i>

9
00:00:23.802 --> 00:00:25.304
<i>He's been branded.</i>

10
00:00:25.404 --> 00:00:27.306
Until we have the confidence

11
00:00:27.439 --> 00:00:28.940
that you're willing
to work with us.

12
00:00:29.040 --> 00:00:30.674
we have to limit your access
to the outside world.

13
00:00:30.675 --> 00:00:32.311
How much more limited
can my access possibly be?

14
00:00:32.411 --> 00:00:35.447
Your visitors are restricted
to the family members

15
00:00:35.547 --> 00:00:37.916
you've already agreed
to talk to. and that's it.

16
00:00:38.016 --> 00:00:39.418
Mr. Voit.

17
00:00:40.819 --> 00:00:42.321
My name is Joshua Ryan.

18
00:00:42.421 --> 00:00:44.823
<i>Deena Ryan was my cousin.</i>

19
00:00:44.923 --> 00:00:47.191
I don't see you yelling for the warden

20
00:00:47.192 --> 00:00:52.663
to let you call the BAU and
tell them you found your Fan.

21
00:00:52.664 --> 00:00:56.034
You do think I'm pathetic.

22
00:00:56.134 --> 00:00:58.001
Now. what did you want
to show me?

23
00:01:03.041 --> 00:01:04.343
I'll fucking kill you.

24
00:01:04.443 --> 00:01:05.877
You're not gonna
fucking kill me.

25
00:01:06.010 --> 00:01:07.412
You're not even gonna
have me arrested

26
00:01:07.512 --> 00:01:10.315
'cause you know I wouldn't
have walked in here

27
00:01:10.415 --> 00:01:12.884
if I didn't have
a plan for this.

28
00:01:15.654 --> 00:01:17.789
Now who's pathetic?

29
00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:25.074
Watch Online Movies and Series for FREE
www.osdb.link/lm

30
00:01:34.406 --> 00:01:35.707
Geez. I mean. with the add-ons.

31
00:01:35.807 --> 00:01:37.041
it's like we're buying
a car here.

32
00:01:37.141 --> 00:01:39.209
Arturo. please.

33
00:01:39.210 --> 00:01:40.412
Stop.

34
00:01:40.545 --> 00:01:42.213
Seriously. at this rate.

35
00:01:42.347 --> 00:01:45.416
we're not gonna get out of here
for less than 12.000 bucks.

36
00:01:45.417 --> 00:01:47.286
You got any cremation options?

37
00:01:47.386 --> 00:01:49.454
No. we just can't.

38
00:01:49.554 --> 00:01:51.589
That's what we're gonna do.

39
00:01:51.590 --> 00:01:54.091
Yes. but I promised Papé

40
00:01:54.092 --> 00:01:55.694
that I'd give him
a proper burial.

41
00:01:55.794 --> 00:01:57.429
He wouldn't want us to take out

42
00:01:57.529 --> 00:02:00.230
a second mortgage to do it.

43
00:02:00.231 --> 00:02:02.434
Please forgive my husband.

44
00:02:02.534 --> 00:02:04.735
I completely understand.

45
00:02:04.736 --> 00:02:07.339
And if I could. I would try
to offer you a better deal.

46
00:02:07.439 --> 00:02:11.109
but. truthfully.
all of our costs have risen.

47
00:02:11.242 --> 00:02:13.578
No. we do understand.

48
00:02:13.678 --> 00:02:14.846
We do.

49
00:02:14.946 --> 00:02:17.949
And Uncle Victor's funeral
was just...

50
00:02:18.049 --> 00:02:20.618
- so lovely.
- Thank you.

51
00:02:20.619 --> 00:02:23.688
Your mother.
she did such wonderful work.

52
00:02:23.788 --> 00:02:25.957
How is she?

53
00:02:26.958 --> 00:02:29.428
Uh. she's passed.

54
00:02:29.561 --> 00:02:30.995
Six months ago.

55
00:02:31.095 --> 00:02:32.797
Oh. I'm so sorry.

56
00:02:32.931 --> 00:02:34.265
Thank you.

57
00:02:34.366 --> 00:02:36.134
Our condolences.

58
00:02:36.267 --> 00:02:37.769
Sweetheart.

59
00:02:37.902 --> 00:02:40.271
Can we just take a little more
time to think about all this?

60
00:02:40.372 --> 00:02:41.640
Uh...

61
00:02:41.773 --> 00:02:43.273
May we call you later?

62
00:02:43.274 --> 00:02:46.545
Of course. And while we don't
do cremation on site.

63
00:02:46.645 --> 00:02:48.780
I can arrange everything.

64
00:02:48.880 --> 00:02:50.449
And you might like
to take a look

65
00:02:50.549 --> 00:02:52.784
at some of these beautiful urns.

66
00:02:55.153 --> 00:02:56.954
- Oh. cool. Thanks.
- Uh. no. we...

67
00:02:56.955 --> 00:02:59.122
we won't be needing that.

68
00:02:59.123 --> 00:03:02.226
Uh. we'll be in touch.

69
00:03:19.978 --> 00:03:23.181
Good afternoon. Mrs. Enright.

70
00:03:25.950 --> 00:03:28.853
The psoriasis on your neck
clear up?

71
00:03:30.422 --> 00:03:31.989
Good.

72
00:03:37.562 --> 00:03:40.131
Good afternoon. This is Marvin.

73
00:03:40.965 --> 00:03:43.768
Yes. from Bancroft Mortuary.

74
00:03:44.736 --> 00:03:49.173
I just wanted to let you know
that Mrs. Enright is ready.

75
00:03:51.109 --> 00:03:53.211
Yes.

76
00:03:53.311 --> 00:03:55.246
8:00 a.m. on Thursday
is perfect.

77
00:03:55.346 --> 00:03:58.383
You have a wonderful
rest of your day.

78
00:04:22.040 --> 00:04:26.878
<i>Chapters of Grief. chapter four.</i>

79
00:04:26.978 --> 00:04:29.781
<i>"Grieving Deliberately."</i>

80
00:04:31.082 --> 00:04:35.186
<i>Too often.
we try to rush our grief.</i>

81
00:04:35.286 --> 00:04:38.056
<i>We simply want
to push through it</i>

82
00:04:38.156 --> 00:04:41.526
<i>so that we may move on
with our everyday lives.</i>

83
00:04:41.626 --> 00:04:46.465
<i>But when it's someone
close to you who passes.</i>

84
00:04:46.565 --> 00:04:49.734
<i>it leaves a wound.</i>

85
00:04:49.834 --> 00:04:53.104
<i>Just like any other
bodily injury.</i>

86
00:04:53.237 --> 00:04:57.809
<i>it requires care and patience.</i>

87
00:04:57.909 --> 00:05:00.311
<i>If you break your ankle
one day.</i>

88
00:05:00.411 --> 00:05:02.613
<i>you're not going to wake up
the next morning</i>

89
00:05:02.614 --> 00:05:05.684
<i>and run a marathon.</i>

90
00:05:05.784 --> 00:05:09.921
<i>So. as you process your grief.</i>

91
00:05:10.021 --> 00:05:12.122
<i>you must remind yourself</i>

92
00:05:12.123 --> 00:05:15.960
<i>that wounds take time to heal</i>

93
00:05:16.094 --> 00:05:19.197
<i>and accept that you are human.</i>

94
00:05:20.364 --> 00:05:22.033
<i>We eat.</i>

95
00:05:22.133 --> 00:05:24.268
<i>We sleep.</i>

96
00:05:25.103 --> 00:05:26.838
<i>We bleed.</i>

97
00:05:27.706 --> 00:05:30.208
<i>We grieve.</i>

98
00:05:30.308 --> 00:05:31.910
<i>All you can do is just</i>

99
00:05:32.010 --> 00:05:35.113
<i>put one foot
in front of the other.</i>

100
00:05:35.213 --> 00:05:38.449
<i>and when you open your eyes
each morning.</i>

101
00:05:38.583 --> 00:05:43.287
<i>accept every waking minute
for what it is:</i>

102
00:05:43.387 --> 00:05:47.726
<i>an essential part
of your grieving journey.</i>

103
00:05:53.932 --> 00:05:55.500
Stop.

104
00:05:55.634 --> 00:05:58.637
- It's okay.
- Stop.

105
00:05:58.770 --> 00:06:00.338
Don't worry.

106
00:06:00.438 --> 00:06:03.642
You're doing great.

107
00:06:03.775 --> 00:06:05.810
Shh.

108
00:06:05.910 --> 00:06:07.812
<i>Like a deep. running river</i>

109
00:06:07.946 --> 00:06:10.314
<i>churning and flowing.</i>

110
00:06:10.414 --> 00:06:15.520
<i>grief tends to resolve itself
on its own terms.</i>

111
00:06:15.620 --> 00:06:18.022
<i>You can choose to fight it...</i>

112
00:06:20.158 --> 00:06:23.327
<i>...resist its chaotic nature.</i>

113
00:06:23.461 --> 00:06:26.329
<i>or choose to embrace it.</i>

114
00:06:26.330 --> 00:06:29.332
<i>And no matter how powerless
you may feel...</i>

115
00:06:31.069 --> 00:06:33.003
<i>...always remember</i>

116
00:06:33.004 --> 00:06:38.843
<i>that you are someone
who deserves love and respect.</i>

117
00:06:39.711 --> 00:06:43.848
<i>And that you are
the only one who decides</i>

118
00:06:43.982 --> 00:06:48.352
<i>whether or not
you will have a good day.</i>

119
00:07:04.268 --> 00:07:06.605
Okay. like you mean it.

120
00:07:06.705 --> 00:07:08.607
You guys. let me hear you.

121
00:07:10.008 --> 00:07:11.541
What?

122
00:07:11.542 --> 00:07:13.712
You call that a roar?
With passion.

123
00:07:13.812 --> 00:07:15.212
- Again.
- I'm sorry.

124
00:07:15.213 --> 00:07:16.547
This is a bit much.

125
00:07:16.648 --> 00:07:18.516
I feel like the claws
are enough.

126
00:07:18.617 --> 00:07:20.751
How dare both of you.

127
00:07:20.752 --> 00:07:22.085
Okay. now they're here.

128
00:07:22.086 --> 00:07:23.587
Okay. everyone.
get ready. get ready.

129
00:07:23.588 --> 00:07:25.724
- Think feral. okay? Here we go.
- Shh. shh.

130
00:07:29.327 --> 00:07:30.929
Congratulations!

131
00:07:31.062 --> 00:07:33.164
Congratulations!

132
00:07:34.032 --> 00:07:36.534
Wow. Thanks.

133
00:07:36.635 --> 00:07:38.637
Okay. your mom told you. right?

134
00:07:38.737 --> 00:07:41.940
I swear I did not.

135
00:07:42.040 --> 00:07:43.941
Your cars are around the corner.

136
00:07:43.942 --> 00:07:45.376
Oh. they were.

137
00:07:45.476 --> 00:07:48.079
Okay. can we work on
our not-at-work stealthiness?

138
00:07:48.179 --> 00:07:50.080
No. no. it's cool.

139
00:07:50.081 --> 00:07:51.850
I like it. Thanks. Auntie P.

140
00:07:51.950 --> 00:07:53.685
So sweet.

141
00:07:53.785 --> 00:07:55.586
Meow.

142
00:07:55.687 --> 00:07:58.857
This is impressive.

143
00:07:59.791 --> 00:08:01.059
Ooh.

144
00:08:01.159 --> 00:08:04.696
Oh. so Spence told me
that he's happy for Henry

145
00:08:04.796 --> 00:08:08.432
but that he can still make
that call to Caltech.

146
00:08:08.532 --> 00:08:11.069
you know.
if he changes his mind.

147
00:08:11.936 --> 00:08:15.539
You have a lot to be proud of.

148
00:08:15.640 --> 00:08:19.644
You know who we're really here
to celebrate. right?

149
00:08:19.778 --> 00:08:21.780
You and Will.

150
00:08:23.281 --> 00:08:25.249
It's-it's been a long road.

151
00:08:30.588 --> 00:08:33.591
Heard you're getting roped
into another Voit sit-down.

152
00:08:33.692 --> 00:08:35.727
Oh. yeah. Should be interesting.

153
00:08:35.827 --> 00:08:37.828
- What does he want?
- No idea.

154
00:08:37.829 --> 00:08:40.264
The guy's gone silent since we
put him in the penalty box.

155
00:08:40.364 --> 00:08:42.734
Yeah.
he-he threw a bit of a tantrum

156
00:08:42.834 --> 00:08:44.468
when we limited his visitation.

157
00:08:44.602 --> 00:08:47.638
but this could be
an olive branch.

158
00:08:47.739 --> 00:08:50.775
Hey. chuckleheads.
What did we say? No shop talk.

159
00:08:50.875 --> 00:08:52.343
- Oh.
- Yeah.

160
00:08:52.476 --> 00:08:54.478
- All right.
- Busted.

161
00:08:54.578 --> 00:08:56.647
Okay. my pretties.
before work consumes us.

162
00:08:56.748 --> 00:08:58.282
let's take a family photo.

163
00:08:58.382 --> 00:09:02.020
Now. this happens
in groups of three.

164
00:09:02.120 --> 00:09:06.257
So. let the first one be
just our fabulous selves.

165
00:09:12.096 --> 00:09:14.332
Okay.

166
00:09:14.432 --> 00:09:16.701
Now a silly one.
No. no. no. Bobcat.

167
00:09:16.835 --> 00:09:19.303
Okay. uh. one. two...

168
00:09:19.403 --> 00:09:21.773
Oh.

169
00:09:24.976 --> 00:09:26.144
Three.

170
00:09:32.616 --> 00:09:34.719
Early this morning.
a teen wilderness troop

171
00:09:34.819 --> 00:09:36.855
was happily traversing
the hills and hollers

172
00:09:36.955 --> 00:09:40.291
of Darrington Nature Reserve in
Gardener County. West Virginia.

173
00:09:40.391 --> 00:09:42.692
when they tragically came
upon the body

174
00:09:42.693 --> 00:09:44.561
of 65-year-old Sharon Fussel.

175
00:09:44.562 --> 00:09:46.865
She joins Janis Kline
as the second woman

176
00:09:46.965 --> 00:09:49.500
in under two weeks
to be found in that area.

177
00:09:49.600 --> 00:09:51.269
Both victims had
their eyes glued open

178
00:09:51.369 --> 00:09:53.237
and their bodies
completely drained of blood.

179
00:09:53.371 --> 00:09:54.839
phlebotomist-style.

180
00:09:55.673 --> 00:09:57.075
Those women don't look dead.

181
00:09:57.208 --> 00:10:00.044
Yeah. more like someone
just shook them awake.

182
00:10:00.144 --> 00:10:01.879
Do we have a time of death
on either?

183
00:10:01.880 --> 00:10:04.715
No. And the local coroner
is just as perplexed

184
00:10:04.816 --> 00:10:06.717
about the state of these bodies
as we are.

185
00:10:06.818 --> 00:10:09.020
Locals should run
a tox screening

186
00:10:09.120 --> 00:10:10.488
for methanol and ethanol.

187
00:10:10.588 --> 00:10:11.890
Embalming fluid?

188
00:10:11.990 --> 00:10:13.391
Yeah. it helps
preserve the bodies.

189
00:10:13.524 --> 00:10:15.725
Maybe he's leaving them
in a state

190
00:10:15.726 --> 00:10:18.129
where he can come back
and enjoy.

191
00:10:18.897 --> 00:10:22.400
The victims are around
the same height. weight.

192
00:10:22.500 --> 00:10:24.567
Unsub has a physical type.

193
00:10:24.568 --> 00:10:27.205
But the victims are
ten years apart.

194
00:10:28.907 --> 00:10:30.941
There's no sign of assault.

195
00:10:30.942 --> 00:10:34.879
And he glued the eyes open
postmortem.

196
00:10:34.979 --> 00:10:36.480
What are you thinking?

197
00:10:37.748 --> 00:10:39.917
Unsubs will often
force their victims

198
00:10:39.918 --> 00:10:41.752
to watch what they're doing.

199
00:10:41.886 --> 00:10:43.754
This guy does it
after he kills them.

200
00:10:43.855 --> 00:10:45.689
Well. he must feel
more comfortable

201
00:10:45.790 --> 00:10:48.559
"interacting" with his victims
once they're dead.

202
00:10:48.659 --> 00:10:50.760
Gardener County has turned
the investigation over

203
00:10:50.761 --> 00:10:52.964
to the West Virginia Staties.

204
00:10:53.097 --> 00:10:55.399
JJ. Tyler. let's interview
friends and family.

205
00:10:55.499 --> 00:10:58.569
Dave. Luke.
review the autopsy reports.

206
00:10:58.669 --> 00:11:01.172
Disturbing this unsub's
dumping ground

207
00:11:01.272 --> 00:11:03.107
isn't gonna slow him down.

208
00:11:06.610 --> 00:11:08.312
<i>Elias.</i>

209
00:11:08.446 --> 00:11:09.981
We got your message.

210
00:11:10.081 --> 00:11:11.983
Let me get this straight...
you want us to break

211
00:11:12.083 --> 00:11:14.952
WITSEC protocol
to check in on your family.

212
00:11:14.953 --> 00:11:16.420
I get it.

213
00:11:16.520 --> 00:11:18.122
It's frowned upon
when government agencies

214
00:11:18.256 --> 00:11:19.858
shit in each other's
litter boxes.

215
00:11:19.958 --> 00:11:21.659
- but given the circumstances...
- Elias.

216
00:11:21.759 --> 00:11:23.294
You'd be doing them... you're
essentially cleaning up...

217
00:11:23.394 --> 00:11:26.330
Elias. one of our own went
into WITSEC. all right?

218
00:11:26.430 --> 00:11:27.465
It's safe.

219
00:11:27.565 --> 00:11:28.632
Yeah.

220
00:11:28.732 --> 00:11:30.633
One of your own.
This is different.

221
00:11:30.634 --> 00:11:33.170
When the world learned my name.
it put them at risk.

222
00:11:33.171 --> 00:11:35.306
You're right. and the Marshals
probably had to move

223
00:11:35.406 --> 00:11:37.041
heaven and earth
to get them new identities.

224
00:11:37.141 --> 00:11:39.510
But. unfortunately. those were
the cards they were dealt.

225
00:11:39.643 --> 00:11:42.380
Cards they were dealt by you.

226
00:11:44.082 --> 00:11:45.549
Now. where is this coming from?

227
00:11:45.649 --> 00:11:47.151
Do you have some reason
to believe

228
00:11:47.251 --> 00:11:49.153
that the Fan is gonna
target your family?

229
00:11:49.253 --> 00:11:52.924
I just want to know
they're safe.

230
00:11:55.593 --> 00:11:57.827
We'll see what we can do.

231
00:12:01.966 --> 00:12:03.367
Yes. Mrs. Beltran.

232
00:12:03.501 --> 00:12:07.438
El Paso Oak is the solid oak
with wheat corners.

233
00:12:08.973 --> 00:12:10.474
Yes. I agree.

234
00:12:10.574 --> 00:12:13.211
And that wouldn't
cost you much more.

235
00:12:14.745 --> 00:12:18.349
Well. let's see.

236
00:12:20.484 --> 00:12:23.854
Would you and your husband
be able to come by

237
00:12:23.988 --> 00:12:26.390
Friday morning?

238
00:12:27.725 --> 00:12:28.859
Perfect.

239
00:12:28.960 --> 00:12:32.563
Now. you have a wonderful
rest of your day.

240
00:12:38.236 --> 00:12:40.404
<i>Chapter five.</i>

241
00:12:40.538 --> 00:12:43.207
<i>"Weathering the Storm."</i>

242
00:12:44.442 --> 00:12:48.446
<i>Losing a loved one
can make us feel powerless.</i>

243
00:12:49.247 --> 00:12:51.916
<i>Like we have no control.</i>

244
00:12:52.016 --> 00:12:55.886
<i>Now. picture yourself alone
on a sailboat</i>

245
00:12:56.020 --> 00:12:58.556
<i>that's crossing the ocean.</i>

246
00:12:58.656 --> 00:13:00.824
<i>Dark storm clouds surround you.</i>

247
00:13:00.925 --> 00:13:03.928
<i>Gale-force winds bearing down.</i>

248
00:13:04.062 --> 00:13:07.398
<i>Waves crashing over the sides.</i>

249
00:13:07.498 --> 00:13:09.767
<i>tossing the boat
left and right.</i>

250
00:13:09.900 --> 00:13:14.405
<i>Do you shut your eyes and hope
for the winds to change?</i>

251
00:13:14.505 --> 00:13:16.240
<i>For the storm to pass?</i>

252
00:13:17.041 --> 00:13:22.245
<i>Or do you take charge
and adjust the sails?</i>

253
00:13:26.584 --> 00:13:29.919
Help me!

254
00:13:29.920 --> 00:13:31.422
Anyone!

255
00:13:31.555 --> 00:13:34.457
Help me!

256
00:13:34.458 --> 00:13:37.260
Please. please. please help me!

257
00:13:37.261 --> 00:13:39.596
Please let me out!

258
00:13:39.597 --> 00:13:42.632
Please. Please.

259
00:13:42.633 --> 00:13:45.003
No.

260
00:13:45.836 --> 00:13:48.272
No more. No.

261
00:13:48.372 --> 00:13:49.740
No more. okay?

262
00:13:49.840 --> 00:13:52.942
No more. No.

263
00:13:52.943 --> 00:13:55.446
What the fuck is...

264
00:13:55.579 --> 00:13:57.648
No.
What the fuck are you doing?

265
00:13:57.781 --> 00:13:59.583
What the fuck is wrong with you?

266
00:13:59.683 --> 00:14:02.086
You need to eat.

267
00:14:10.961 --> 00:14:12.596
You sick fuck!

268
00:14:21.972 --> 00:14:23.507
That wasn't so bad.

269
00:14:28.446 --> 00:14:32.750
You're only making this harder
on yourself. my dear.

270
00:14:44.462 --> 00:14:45.496
<i>We're so sorry</i>

271
00:14:45.596 --> 00:14:46.630
<i>for your loss. Mr. Fussel.</i>

272
00:14:46.730 --> 00:14:47.865
When they brought me in

273
00:14:47.998 --> 00:14:50.534
to identify Sharon.

274
00:14:50.634 --> 00:14:52.903
she still looked...

275
00:14:53.003 --> 00:14:54.572
so alive.

276
00:14:54.672 --> 00:14:58.176
Like I just needed to shake her.

277
00:14:58.309 --> 00:15:00.544
she'd get up and walk out.

278
00:15:01.512 --> 00:15:03.713
Mr. Fussel. what do you remember

279
00:15:03.714 --> 00:15:05.949
about the day
that Sharon went missing?

280
00:15:07.951 --> 00:15:10.954
It was the day
after my birthday.

281
00:15:11.055 --> 00:15:13.190
Two months ago.

282
00:15:13.191 --> 00:15:16.559
We'd just moved into
a senior-living community.

283
00:15:16.560 --> 00:15:19.097
which Sharon wasn't
too thrilled about.

284
00:15:20.498 --> 00:15:21.932
She'd gone out to the mailbox.

285
00:15:22.032 --> 00:15:24.701
which was
around the block there.

286
00:15:24.702 --> 00:15:26.637
That was the last time
I saw her.

287
00:15:27.405 --> 00:15:31.708
You know. I didn't think that
we needed to spend the money

288
00:15:31.709 --> 00:15:34.512
on one of those
security systems with cameras.

289
00:15:34.612 --> 00:15:36.247
This isn't your fault.

290
00:15:37.047 --> 00:15:40.584
Can you think of anyone who
would want to hurt your wife?

291
00:15:40.684 --> 00:15:42.986
Not a soul.

292
00:15:43.087 --> 00:15:44.722
Everybody adored her.

293
00:15:46.056 --> 00:15:48.326
I'm trying not to think about

294
00:15:48.426 --> 00:15:50.928
what he might have done
to her. you know?

295
00:15:51.762 --> 00:15:53.030
It's all so sickening.

296
00:15:55.399 --> 00:15:57.635
Why would he bother
to change her clothes?

297
00:15:58.936 --> 00:16:02.740
The clothes they found her in...
they weren't hers?

298
00:16:02.840 --> 00:16:04.408
No.

299
00:16:04.508 --> 00:16:06.910
When she left the house.
she was wearing. like.

300
00:16:07.010 --> 00:16:08.779
her jogging outfit.

301
00:16:09.913 --> 00:16:12.081
<i>So. we confirmed
with Janis Kline's son</i>

302
00:16:12.082 --> 00:16:13.616
the clothes she was wearing

303
00:16:13.617 --> 00:16:15.419
when she was found
weren't hers. either.

304
00:16:15.519 --> 00:16:18.289
Which means he's re-dressing
the victims postmortem.

305
00:16:18.389 --> 00:16:19.857
Now. I'm no fashion expert.

306
00:16:19.957 --> 00:16:23.093
but there don't seem to be
any striking similarities

307
00:16:23.194 --> 00:16:26.063
between the clothes
on Sharon and Janis.

308
00:16:26.164 --> 00:16:28.132
Yeah. now that you mention it.

309
00:16:28.232 --> 00:16:30.634
the style of the clothes
are distinct...

310
00:16:30.734 --> 00:16:32.436
from different decades. maybe.

311
00:16:32.570 --> 00:16:33.871
I see your point.

312
00:16:33.971 --> 00:16:36.140
You'd expect an unsub
to use a surrogate

313
00:16:36.240 --> 00:16:40.144
to re-create a specific fantasy
over and over.

314
00:16:41.312 --> 00:16:44.515
He's definitely preserving them
to be modeled for something.

315
00:16:44.615 --> 00:16:46.784
M.E. ran additional tox screens.

316
00:16:46.917 --> 00:16:50.288
and both victims.
along with embalming fluid.

317
00:16:50.388 --> 00:16:53.224
had near-lethal levels
of magnesium in their systems.

318
00:16:53.324 --> 00:16:55.493
I thought the cause of death
was exsanguination.

319
00:16:55.593 --> 00:16:56.960
It was.

320
00:16:57.060 --> 00:16:59.363
That means this guy was
force-feeding them magnesium

321
00:16:59.463 --> 00:17:01.965
- over several days.
- Why magnesium?

322
00:17:02.800 --> 00:17:06.370
It enhances hydration.
uh. reduces inflammation.

323
00:17:06.470 --> 00:17:09.473
Some people say it makes
your skin more radiant.

324
00:17:09.573 --> 00:17:12.676
All the better
for him to admire.

325
00:17:15.446 --> 00:17:18.416
<i>Grief introduces chaotic forces</i>

326
00:17:18.516 --> 00:17:21.785
<i>that can disrupt
our daily routines.</i>

327
00:17:21.885 --> 00:17:26.657
<i>But those turbulent forces
can be channeled.</i>

328
00:17:26.790 --> 00:17:30.794
<i>Rather than trying
to ignore your grief.</i>

329
00:17:30.894 --> 00:17:33.697
<i>try listening to it.</i>

330
00:17:34.798 --> 00:17:38.202
<i>The pain you feel is
the residual effect</i>

331
00:17:38.336 --> 00:17:40.404
<i>of loving someone.</i>

332
00:17:41.171 --> 00:17:43.840
<i>Just because they're
no longer with you</i>

333
00:17:43.841 --> 00:17:46.043
<i>doesn't mean
they can't continue</i>

334
00:17:46.176 --> 00:17:49.280
<i>to motivate and inspire you.</i>

335
00:17:50.214 --> 00:17:54.518
<i>But. in order to properly
channel those emotions.</i>

336
00:17:54.652 --> 00:17:58.021
<i>you should remember
this timeless maxim:</i>

337
00:17:58.121 --> 00:18:02.225
<i>We must accept
what we cannot control.</i>

338
00:18:02.226 --> 00:18:05.728
"We must accept

339
00:18:05.729 --> 00:18:08.899
what we cannot control."

340
00:18:24.648 --> 00:18:27.918
<i>Voit wants us to find
his family in WITSEC.</i>

341
00:18:28.018 --> 00:18:29.552
What prompted this?

342
00:18:29.553 --> 00:18:32.890
Well. we think that it might
have something to do with...

343
00:18:32.990 --> 00:18:34.725
this man.

344
00:18:35.659 --> 00:18:38.762
He checked in as Joshua Ryan.
cousin of Alex. Deena's father.

345
00:18:38.896 --> 00:18:40.564
- Mm-hmm.
- He visited three times

346
00:18:40.664 --> 00:18:42.366
in three days.

347
00:18:42.466 --> 00:18:45.035
Watch what happened
on his last visit.

348
00:18:46.437 --> 00:18:49.607
We think that's a photo
of Voit's family.

349
00:18:49.707 --> 00:18:51.108
That's what got him spooked?

350
00:18:51.208 --> 00:18:53.911
Look. Voit tried to get
a message to the Fan.

351
00:18:54.011 --> 00:18:56.547
inviting him to come
visit him in prison.

352
00:18:57.348 --> 00:18:58.781
What if he did just that?

353
00:18:58.782 --> 00:19:01.319
He didn't sign the release
for the audio recording.

354
00:19:01.419 --> 00:19:03.287
and he came in
with ghost glasses.

355
00:19:03.387 --> 00:19:04.988
They emitted an infrared light

356
00:19:05.088 --> 00:19:07.290
that blew out
the security cameras.

357
00:19:07.291 --> 00:19:08.458
Holy shit.

358
00:19:08.459 --> 00:19:09.960
- This is him.
- Yeah.

359
00:19:10.060 --> 00:19:12.430
Yeah. that's not all.
Look at this.

360
00:19:13.764 --> 00:19:14.965
See that keychain?

361
00:19:15.098 --> 00:19:16.300
It's an anime character.

362
00:19:16.434 --> 00:19:19.101
Extremely similar to the artwork

363
00:19:19.102 --> 00:19:22.272
that we found
in Victoria Everman's apartment.

364
00:19:22.373 --> 00:19:25.274
- A trophy from his first kill.
- I think so.

365
00:19:25.275 --> 00:19:27.276
Do we really think it's possible

366
00:19:27.277 --> 00:19:29.947
the Fan could actually be
Alex Ryan's cousin?

367
00:19:30.047 --> 00:19:33.484
I think it's far more likely
the Fan pulled one over on Alex.

368
00:19:33.617 --> 00:19:36.486
but either way. we need to get
Alex in for questioning now.

369
00:19:36.487 --> 00:19:37.955
We're on it.

370
00:19:46.730 --> 00:19:50.934
Does it matter if your Fan knows
exactly where they are or not?

371
00:19:51.769 --> 00:19:55.105
Because. if there's a will.
there's a way.

372
00:19:55.906 --> 00:19:57.307
It's what I've been saying

373
00:19:57.441 --> 00:20:00.944
ever since they locked you up
in this place.

374
00:20:11.021 --> 00:20:14.692
I noticed you didn't mention
to Dr. Lewis

375
00:20:14.792 --> 00:20:17.661
that he showed up
to threaten your family.

376
00:20:17.761 --> 00:20:19.530
I asked her to check on them.

377
00:20:19.630 --> 00:20:21.865
Eh. if I didn't know
any better. I would say

378
00:20:21.999 --> 00:20:24.501
- you're up to your old tricks.
- I'm not.

379
00:20:24.502 --> 00:20:26.537
You know how I know?

380
00:20:26.637 --> 00:20:28.539
Because you go quiet

381
00:20:28.639 --> 00:20:31.375
and you start lying
to everybody.

382
00:20:31.475 --> 00:20:35.312
including yourself.

383
00:20:47.658 --> 00:20:51.894
As anyone who has been forced
to read Ayn Rand will tell you.

384
00:20:51.895 --> 00:20:54.031
awfulness comes in three parts.

385
00:20:54.131 --> 00:20:55.898
Another body
in Darrington Reserve?

386
00:20:55.899 --> 00:20:58.568
Nope. but a stone's throw away
in Fielder County.

387
00:20:58.569 --> 00:21:00.237
Our unsub's got
a new dumping ground.

388
00:21:00.337 --> 00:21:02.071
I'll get Dave
and head over there now.

389
00:21:02.072 --> 00:21:03.306
Yeah.

390
00:21:03.407 --> 00:21:05.374
Thanks for coming in. Mr. Ryan.

391
00:21:05.375 --> 00:21:07.811
I know what
you're going to ask me.

392
00:21:08.712 --> 00:21:09.647
Do you?

393
00:21:09.747 --> 00:21:11.582
It's about my cousin. isn't it?

394
00:21:12.450 --> 00:21:14.117
Yes. it is.

395
00:21:15.553 --> 00:21:17.254
Look...

396
00:21:18.221 --> 00:21:21.223
I know that me and my ex-wife
are the only ones

397
00:21:21.224 --> 00:21:24.227
that were given permission
to speak to Voit...

398
00:21:25.529 --> 00:21:28.265
...but I swear
I-I couldn't do it.

399
00:21:29.166 --> 00:21:32.770
And when Joshua reached out.
it was like...

400
00:21:32.870 --> 00:21:34.972
the universe stepping in
to help me.

401
00:21:36.907 --> 00:21:39.576
I hadn't seen Joshua in 20...

402
00:21:39.577 --> 00:21:41.244
I don't know. maybe 30 years.

403
00:21:41.378 --> 00:21:43.614
And in all that time.
he got himself a...

404
00:21:43.714 --> 00:21:46.249
a PhD in criminology.

405
00:21:47.518 --> 00:21:49.219
Really?

406
00:21:49.319 --> 00:21:51.455
And so. I'm assuming that Joshua

407
00:21:51.589 --> 00:21:54.057
offered to speak to Voit
on your behalf?

408
00:21:55.292 --> 00:21:58.427
He said he wanted to write books
on serial killers.

409
00:21:58.428 --> 00:22:01.632
So it seemed like a good plan.

410
00:22:02.633 --> 00:22:07.104
After your cousin's visits.
did he reach out to you again?

411
00:22:07.204 --> 00:22:08.606
No. not yet. Why?

412
00:22:09.807 --> 00:22:11.642
Mr. Ryan. we don't believe
that the person

413
00:22:11.775 --> 00:22:15.479
that you interacted with was
actually your cousin Joshua.

414
00:22:18.081 --> 00:22:19.750
What?

415
00:22:21.218 --> 00:22:23.353
He knew everything
about my family.

416
00:22:24.287 --> 00:22:25.889
I'm sure that he did.

417
00:22:25.989 --> 00:22:29.126
Do you have any contact
information for this man?

418
00:22:31.094 --> 00:22:32.996
Uh. we...

419
00:22:33.096 --> 00:22:36.133
we only wrote emails
back and forth.

420
00:22:37.234 --> 00:22:41.204
The last one bounced...
bounced back for some reason.

421
00:22:47.811 --> 00:22:49.146
Who would do this?

422
00:22:59.489 --> 00:23:00.990
They get an I.D. on the victim?

423
00:23:00.991 --> 00:23:03.293
State Police identified her
as Chloe Watts.

424
00:23:03.393 --> 00:23:05.563
She was reported missing
three weeks ago.

425
00:23:05.663 --> 00:23:08.098
Same as the two other victims
over in Gardener.

426
00:23:08.198 --> 00:23:10.200
Eyes glued open.

427
00:23:13.170 --> 00:23:15.372
I can't be certain of cause
or time of death.

428
00:23:15.505 --> 00:23:17.841
but the staging
is clearly the same.

429
00:23:22.112 --> 00:23:23.914
How old was she?

430
00:23:24.047 --> 00:23:25.315
Forty-three.

431
00:23:25.415 --> 00:23:27.718
Well. finally.
a distinct pattern emerges.

432
00:23:27.851 --> 00:23:31.387
Each victim is getting younger
by a decade.

433
00:23:31.388 --> 00:23:33.557
You know. and the clothing style

434
00:23:33.691 --> 00:23:35.893
seems to get more dated
with each victim.

435
00:23:35.993 --> 00:23:37.561
It's as if he's
honoring someone.

436
00:23:37.661 --> 00:23:41.231
like a wife
or a family member who died.

437
00:23:41.364 --> 00:23:43.566
And if that's the case.

438
00:23:43.567 --> 00:23:45.903
these clothes
might very well be hers.

439
00:23:47.605 --> 00:23:49.106
They haven't been soaked
in bleach.

440
00:23:49.239 --> 00:23:51.273
That woman's DNA
might still be on them.

441
00:23:51.274 --> 00:23:52.742
Yeah. that's what
I'm betting on.

442
00:23:52.743 --> 00:23:54.410
Dr. Toomey.
we're gonna need to run

443
00:23:54.411 --> 00:23:56.279
a fiber analysis on her clothes.

444
00:23:56.379 --> 00:23:58.081
Absolutely.

445
00:25:02.312 --> 00:25:04.214
Oh. fuck

446
00:26:23.226 --> 00:26:25.628
I have so much to tell you.

447
00:27:30.861 --> 00:27:33.563
<i>Dad. stop talking.</i>

448
00:27:33.663 --> 00:27:34.764
Okay.

449
00:27:34.898 --> 00:27:36.399
I can't drive and listen
at the same time.

450
00:27:36.533 --> 00:27:39.736
No. hey. hey.
you are doing great.

451
00:27:39.837 --> 00:27:41.437
What's the point of this?

452
00:27:41.438 --> 00:27:43.440
Driverless cars
are like two years away.

453
00:27:43.573 --> 00:27:46.609
Oh. my God. do you know
what driving represents?

454
00:27:46.709 --> 00:27:49.579
Our addiction to fossil fuels?

455
00:27:50.580 --> 00:27:52.582
Driving represents freedom.

456
00:27:52.715 --> 00:27:54.417
Hey.

457
00:27:54.517 --> 00:27:57.454
A couple years. your world is
going to open up.

458
00:27:57.587 --> 00:27:59.689
and there's gonna be no more
homework. no more curfew...

459
00:27:59.789 --> 00:28:02.159
No angsty parents
peeking over my shoulder.

460
00:28:02.259 --> 00:28:04.127
No angsty parents.

461
00:28:04.227 --> 00:28:05.963
Life is gonna
give you room to run.

462
00:28:06.063 --> 00:28:07.796
and I'm not gonna be here
to ride shotgun.

463
00:28:07.797 --> 00:28:11.668
so I need to know that you are
ready to take the wheel. okay?

464
00:28:11.768 --> 00:28:13.170
Got it.

465
00:28:13.937 --> 00:28:15.305
One little problem.

466
00:28:15.405 --> 00:28:16.974
- Hmm?
- I don't have my permit.

467
00:28:17.107 --> 00:28:18.608
What do we tell Mom?

468
00:28:19.576 --> 00:28:21.611
It'll be our secret.

469
00:28:23.313 --> 00:28:25.582
What she doesn't know
can't hurt her.

470
00:28:26.449 --> 00:28:28.551
Right. Okay.

471
00:28:28.651 --> 00:28:30.452
- Okay.
- Hands at ten and two.

472
00:28:30.453 --> 00:28:33.290
And just try to lay off
the brake this time. all right?

473
00:28:33.390 --> 00:28:36.493
Yeah. Dad. I got it.

474
00:28:47.971 --> 00:28:49.706
Elias.

475
00:28:50.941 --> 00:28:53.376
Elias. we know
the Fan visited you

476
00:28:53.476 --> 00:28:55.512
and threatened your family.

477
00:28:55.645 --> 00:28:57.414
He had a picture of them.

478
00:28:57.514 --> 00:28:59.816
It could've been a part
of a court record.

479
00:28:59.917 --> 00:29:02.319
He could've lifted it
off a police server.

480
00:29:02.419 --> 00:29:05.022
Director of the U.S. Marshals
assured me

481
00:29:05.122 --> 00:29:07.724
that whatever threat
the Fan made was a bluff.

482
00:29:07.824 --> 00:29:10.859
Your family's new identities
have never been compromised.

483
00:29:10.860 --> 00:29:13.496
Nevertheless.
the Marshals are increasing

484
00:29:13.596 --> 00:29:16.499
the protective detail
on your family as we speak.

485
00:29:16.599 --> 00:29:17.700
They are safe.

486
00:29:17.800 --> 00:29:19.335
And you can help us.

487
00:29:19.336 --> 00:29:22.205
All right? Because you just
sat down with this man.

488
00:29:22.305 --> 00:29:24.007
Tell us what you talked about.

489
00:29:26.910 --> 00:29:28.545
I need to see them first.

490
00:29:29.312 --> 00:29:31.814
We swear we would if we could.

491
00:29:31.915 --> 00:29:35.217
but cooperating with the BAU
also helps ensure their safety.

492
00:29:35.218 --> 00:29:37.687
Yeah. or it just plays
into his hands.

493
00:29:37.787 --> 00:29:39.822
All right.

494
00:29:39.923 --> 00:29:42.159
I know you're scared.

495
00:29:42.259 --> 00:29:44.061
Because even though
you pride yourself

496
00:29:44.161 --> 00:29:47.030
on being able to profile
serial killer behavior.

497
00:29:47.130 --> 00:29:50.400
you have been wrong about
the Fan from the very start.

498
00:29:50.500 --> 00:29:52.369
You underestimated the pace
of his evolution.

499
00:29:52.469 --> 00:29:54.171
You misinterpreted
his motivations.

500
00:29:54.271 --> 00:29:56.473
This guy is creeping around
in your blind spot.

501
00:29:56.573 --> 00:29:58.942
He knows it. and that's why
he can provoke you.

502
00:29:59.042 --> 00:30:01.378
That could be part of his game. too.

503
00:30:01.478 --> 00:30:02.545
like a shell game.

504
00:30:02.679 --> 00:30:04.713
Right?
While we're focusing on you

505
00:30:04.714 --> 00:30:06.083
and your family. he's free

506
00:30:06.216 --> 00:30:08.451
- to pursue his real goal.
- Yeah.

507
00:30:08.551 --> 00:30:11.588
And if you're right. then
everything he shared with me

508
00:30:11.688 --> 00:30:14.724
is just gonna lead you
into a trap. isn't it?

509
00:30:23.666 --> 00:30:25.002
Fresh from the West Virginia
Crime Lab oven.

